ltures Bruce Lee inherited, the milieu he occupied, the martial art he developed, the films he made, and the world he left behind. A unique blend of cultural history and biography, Like Water unearths the cultural strands that Lee intertwined in his rise to a new kind of global stardom. Moving from the gold rush in California and the British occupation of Hong Kong, to the Cold War and the deployment of American troops across Asia, Maeda builds depth and complexity to this larger-than-life figure. His cultural chronology of Bruce Lee reveals Lee to be both a product of his time and a harbinger of a more connected future. Nearly half a century after his tragic death, Bruce Lee remains an inspiring symbol of innovation and determination, with an enduring legacy as the first Asian American global superstar.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChinese American actorsvBiography. 0aMartial artistszChinazHong KongvBiography. 0aMartial artistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aMartial arts filmsxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh  aChinese film industry.  aCultural hybridity.  aHong Kong cinema.  aMartial arts films.  aMartial arts.  aMigration.  aTranspacific.  aanti-asian racism.  aasian film star.  aasian films.  aasian stereotypes.  athe green hornet.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479812899.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479812899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479812899/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles